I was having the same issue, apparently it stems from starting off the process with bunk key and trying to jump right into the KMS activator. I think a major issue comes from lack of description on what the buttons themselves do, so I'll run that down quickly then address the fix to the 30 day issue.

"Install / Uninstall KMService"
This is pretty straight forward, it installs the KMS Activator. If you try and run any of the other processes it will kick it over to an emulator. Which should work fine, however installing the prog is a surefire way to avoid emulation glitches.

"Activation Office 2010 VL"
Clicking this button is what creates the dummy keys and faux activation which gives you the 180 day trial.

"Activation Check Office 2010"
This will check the status of your activated keys, letting you know how long you have left on your trial period. So if you're not sure if you have the 30 or the 180 days, or if you're wondering how many more days you have before you need to run the activator again click this button.

"Install / Uninstall KMService"
This is pretty straight forward, it installs the KMS Activator. If you try and run any of the other processes it will kick it over to an emulator. Which should work fine, however installing the prog is a surefire way to avoid emulation glitches.

"Activation Office 2010 VL"
Clicking this button is what creates the dummy keys and faux activation which gives you the 180 day trial.

"Key Manager Office 2010 VL"
This button will take you to a menu that will let you delete active keys for each Office product. If you find yourself in the situation you need to delete keys do so according to what package you installed. i.e. If you just installed Word, delete the Word key. However if you installed the Office suite, delete the Office key. Don't go line by line deleting Word, Excel, etc.

"Rearm Office 2010"
When your 180 days are up, or if at any point you want to go back to a fresh 180 day trial, this is the button you'll need to click. Think of it as a reset button. If at any point you want to get back to 180 trial, you'd click this first, then the "Activation Office 2010 VL" button.

Now based on the above explanation if you're only getting the 30 day activation you should know what to do. However if you're still somewhat of a n00b and or you're high, I'll spell it out for you ;) You're only getting the 30 day activation because your original keys suck. You need to click the "Key Manager Office 2010 VL" button to delete your bunk key. I for example had the "Professional Plus 2010" suite installed, so I just selected that option and the keys were deleted. Then you chose the "Rearm Office 2010" button to reset everything, and lastly select the "Activation Office 2010 VL" button to implement your 180 trial. To verify that all worked, click the "Activation Check Office 2010" button and if it says 180 days, congrats. If it still say 30 days, you fail at following instructions. Re-read this information from the beginning.

I hope this clears up some confusion.
